---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navigation from '../components/Navigation.astro';
import { getUrl, getAssetUrl } from '../utils/url';
---

<BaseLayout title="Historical Timeline">
  <Navigation />

  <main class="timeline-page">
    <div class="timeline-hero">
      <img src={getAssetUrl("assets/image-9.png")} alt="The Continuum of Creativity" />
      <div class="timeline-hero-overlay">
        <h1>The Continuum of Creativity</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">From Ancient Tools to Generative AI</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="timeline-intro">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="lead">
          Throughout history, new creative technologies have consistently provoked anxiety, resistance, and institutional gatekeeping.
          Yet each transformation ultimately expanded human creative capacity rather than diminishing it. This timeline traces the
          recurring pattern of technological disruption and eventual normalization in creative practice.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="timeline">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">Ancient</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Scribes and Oral Tradition</h3>
            <p>
              Ancient scribes in Egypt, Mesopotamia, and Rome acted not as mere transcribers but as co-authors, refining language and
              adapting texts for cultural contexts. The transition from oral to written tradition sparked debates about authenticity and
              the loss of living knowledge.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1st Century</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Biblical Dictation</h3>
            <p>
              The Apostle Paul and other biblical figures relied on scribes who shaped the final texts. Tertius, who penned Romans,
              and other scribes were creative partners in authorship, challenging modern notions of singular authorship.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1450s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Gutenberg's Printing Press</h3>
            <p>
              Johannes Gutenberg's printing press revolutionized text production, but 15th-century traditionalists feared that texts
              not painstakingly copied by monks would lack authenticity and spiritual value. The technology was seen as a threat to
              the sacred craft of manuscript illumination.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1500s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Dürer and Early Copyright</h3>
            <p>
              Albrecht Dürer secured an "Imperial Privilege" to protect his engravings from unauthorized copying, establishing one
              of the first forms of artistic copyright. His monogram became one of the earliest artist trademarks, asserting
              ownership over creative output.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1700s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Statute of Anne</h3>
            <p>
              The Statute of Anne (1710) established the first copyright law, granting authors rights to their works. This marked
              the beginning of modern intellectual property law and the legal recognition of individual authorship.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1800s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Photography vs. Painting</h3>
            <p>
              The invention of photography caused panic among painters who saw it as the death of their art form. Critics questioned
              whether photography could be considered "true art." Today, nobody demands that photographers document every chemical
              used in developing their images.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1917</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Duchamp's Fountain</h3>
            <p>
              Marcel Duchamp's <em>Fountain</em> challenged fundamental assumptions about authorship by presenting a mass-produced
              urinal as art. It raised the question: does authorship lie in technical skill or conceptual vision? This debate
              continues in discussions of AI-generated art.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1920s-40s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Surrealist Automatism</h3>
            <p>
              Surrealists embraced "automatic writing" and other techniques that deliberately bypassed conscious control. André
              Breton and others argued that true creativity emerged from the unconscious, celebrating opacity rather than
              demanding transparency.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1960s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>The Death of the Author</h3>
            <p>
              Roland Barthes published "The Death of the Author" (1967), arguing that meaning is created by readers, not authors.
              Michel Foucault introduced the "author-function," reframing authorship as a social construct rather than a natural fact.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1970s-80s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Word Processors</h3>
            <p>
              The introduction of word processors sparked fears that writing would become mechanical and that the craft of
              composition would be lost. Critics worried about the loss of the intimate connection between hand and page.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">1990s-2000s</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Digital Sampling and Remix Culture</h3>
            <p>
              Digital sampling in music and the rise of remix culture challenged traditional notions of originality and authorship.
              Legal battles over sampling paralleled contemporary debates about AI training on copyrighted material.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">2022</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Zarya of the Dawn</h3>
            <p>
              Kris Kashtanova's graphic novel received copyright for the human-written narrative but was denied for AI-generated
              images, establishing a precedent that AI outputs alone cannot be copyrighted without sufficient human authorship.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">2023-2024</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>The AI Disclosure Debate</h3>
            <p>
              Publishers, academic institutions, and creative industries grapple with how to handle AI-generated content.
              Mandatory disclosure policies emerge, creating unprecedented demands for documentation of creative processes.
              Artists and writers face rejection of AI-assisted work, regardless of quality.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-marker">2025</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>A Slice of American Cheese</h3>
            <p>
              Kent Keirsey's work received copyright only after exhaustively documenting 34 distinct verbal instructions given
              to AI, setting a new standard for the burden of proof in AI-assisted creativity and complicating the definition
              of "human creativity."
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timeline-item future">
          <div class="timeline-marker">Future</div>
          <div class="timeline-content">
            <h3>Centaur and Cyborg Collaboration</h3>
            <p>
              The future of authorship moves beyond the human-versus-machine binary toward hybrid models of creation. Humans
              and AI collaborate as co-creators, with creators maintaining full autonomy over their methods while being judged
              on the merit of their final products.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="timeline-conclusion">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>The Pattern Is Clear</h2>
        <p>
          Each technological disruption follows the same arc: initial resistance and moral panic, institutional attempts at control,
          gradual normalization, and ultimate expansion of creative capacity. The debate over AI and creative disclosure is not new—it's
          the latest iteration of a timeless tension between innovation and tradition.
        </p>
        <a href={getUrl("/conclusion")} class="cta-button">Read the Conclusion</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .timeline-page {
    min-height: 100vh;
  }

  .timeline-hero {
    position: relative;
    height: 60vh;
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .timeline-hero img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;
    filter: brightness(0.5);
  }

  .timeline-hero-overlay {
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    padding: 3rem 2rem;
    background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(10, 10, 10, 0.9), transparent);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .timeline-hero-overlay h1 {
    font-size: 3.5rem;
    color: var(--warm-beige);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.8);
  }

  .subtitle {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    color: var(--accent-gold);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .container {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 2rem;
  }

  .timeline-intro {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    background-color: var(--warm-beige);
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    line-height: 1.9;
    color: var(--dark-burgundy);
    text-align: center;
    max-width: 900px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .timeline {
    padding: 4rem 0;
    background-color: var(--light-beige);
    position: relative;
  }

  .timeline::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 50%;
    top: 0;
    bottom: 0;
    width: 4px;
    background: linear-gradient(to bottom, var(--burgundy), var(--accent-gold));
    transform: translateX(-50%);
  }

  .timeline-item {
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 2rem;
  }

  .timeline-item:nth-child(odd) {
    flex-direction: row;
  }

  .timeline-item:nth-child(even) {
    flex-direction: row-reverse;
  }

  .timeline-marker {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 150px;
    text-align: center;
    background-color: var(--burgundy);
    color: var(--warm-beige);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
    font-size: 1rem;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 8px rgba(74, 31, 31, 0.3);
  }

  .timeline-content {
    flex: 1;
    background-color: var(--warm-beige);
    padding: 2rem;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 2px solid var(--burgundy);
    box-shadow: 0 4px 12px rgba(74, 31, 31, 0.2);
  }

  .timeline-content h3 {
    font-size: 1.8rem;
    color: var(--dark-burgundy);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .timeline-content p {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--dark-burgundy);
  }

  .timeline-item.future .timeline-marker {
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--burgundy), var(--accent-gold));
  }

  .timeline-item.future .timeline-content {
    border-color: var(--accent-gold);
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--warm-beige), var(--light-beige));
  }

  .timeline-conclusion {
    padding: 6rem 0;
    background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--burgundy), var(--dark-burgundy));
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--warm-beige);
  }

  .timeline-conclusion h2 {
    font-size: 3rem;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .timeline-conclusion p {
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    line-height: 1.9;
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto 2rem;
    opacity: 0.95;
  }

  .cta-button {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 1rem 3rem;
    background-color: var(--warm-beige);
    color: var(--dark-burgundy);
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 2px solid var(--accent-gold);
    transition: all 0.3s ease;
    font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  }

  .cta-button:hover {
    background-color: var(--accent-gold);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
    box-shadow: 0 6px 20px rgba(212, 165, 116, 0.4);
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .timeline::before {
      left: 20px;
    }

    .timeline-item,
    .timeline-item:nth-child(even) {
      flex-direction: column;
      padding-left: 60px;
    }

    .timeline-marker {
      position: absolute;
      left: 0;
      width: 100px;
    }

    .timeline-hero-overlay h1 {
      font-size: 2rem;
    }

    .subtitle {
      font-size: 1.2rem;
    }

    .timeline-conclusion h2 {
      font-size: 2rem;
    }
  }
</style>
